SkyComment: Mostly clear. Only a few puffy white clouds visible. Other than the large light dome in the western sky, all other light domes are very minor and subtle extending no more than 7 to 10 degrees above the horizon. Light dome to the West and NNW extends 15 to 20 degrees above the horizon and is likely due to the cities of Hollidaysburg and Altoona. Other lights were observed to the north and east - likely from park cabins, maintenance buildings as well as boat launch and residences as seen across the lake.
LocationComment: Open Grassy Area between parking lots 3 and 4 in day use area. Low ridges and trees do not extend more than 10 degrees above the horizon, except large tree in grassy area to the WSW.

SkyComment: 100% Clear. Light domes are very minor and subtle as seen to the ESE (Lewistown) and to NNW (State College) just above the tree tops approximately 15 degrees above the horizon. The trees and ridges do keep lights from surrounding communities from protruding onto the area. Some outdoor walk-way lights was noted from the park office. Some car lights were noted from passing cars traveling on Route 305 (Greenwood Road). It is not known if the Blacksmith Shop parking lot lights are continuously on during seasonal hours. They were off during the survey. Treetops and ridgelines could be seen as silhouettes. Objects/obstacles on ground could only be slightly discerned. Otherwise area is appreciably dark.  Winter portion of Milky Way was visible to the unaided eye.
LocationComment: Rural Location. Baseball field ENE of Greenwood Lake. Except to the SW, the area is completely surrounded by trees and ridges.

SkyComment: 100% Clear. Transparent sky. Sky is semi-dark with bright dome to the SSW - most likely created by CalPine Power Plant and the towns of Delta and West Bangor. Once dark adapted, surface objects are clearly apparent or appear as silhouettes. Skyglow is at treetop level or a few degrees above the tree tops.
LocationComment: Semi-rural location. Sky was clear and transparent. Area is surrounded on all sides by trees which aids in blocking much of the horizon glow. Trees extend upwards to 25° above the horizon to the east and upwards to 10° to the west. Restroom facility has a dim outside light. Maintenance facility has a security light. Fixture is not full cut-off which gives off enough ambient light to illuminate part of the parking area and areas behind restroom facility.

SkyComment: 100% Clear. Sky is bright with significant light domes in all directions likely due to Marietta to the north, Red Lion / Dallastown to the south and southwest, York to the west, and Wrightsville, Columbia and Lancaster to the east. Once dark adapted, surface objects were clearly apparent.
LocationComment: Suburban location. Hilltop Pavilion area. Good horizons with unobstructed views. Not appreciably dark.

SkyComment: Sky was clear and transparent. Area is surrounded on all sides by trees which aids in blocking much of the horizon glow. Trees extend upwards to 20° above the southern horizon and upwards to 10° to the east. Lighted bathhouse/restroom facility to NNW is visible, but little if any light spills onto the playground area. No other outside lights were noted and no active campers were inside the park area. During active season more light from campers would likely be noted.     Sky is semi-dark with bright light domes to the NNW, NNE, and SSE - most likely created by York, Harrisburg, and Mechanicsburg. WSW sky was notably darker. Once dark adapted, surface objects, swings, benches and sandy volleyball court was clearly apparent or appear as silhouettes. Skyglow protrudes above treetop level around perimeter of much of the site.
LocationComment: Semi-rural location. State Park Conewago Day Use Area.

SkyComment: 100% Clear. Skies were very transparent. The Winter Milky Way passing overhead and north of Orion was plainly visible with a mottled appearance. Although fainter than the Summer Milky Way, the extent of the Winter Milky Way could be discerned from NW to SW. The Andromeda Galaxy in the northwest sky was plainly visible to the naked eye.
LocationComment: Semi-rural location, Forest. There were no significant light domes, but tree tops could be seen. Any light domes present did not protrude any more than 5 to 10 degrees. The southern sky to the zenith was appreciably the darkest.

SkyComment: 100% Clear. Light domes were visible along all horizons except to the south and southwest where the sky appeared darkest. Light domes extended above the trees and ridges 10 to 20 degrees. The light dome to the west was likely due to the city of Johnstown. Light domes extending from the northwest to the north and northeast were likely the result of the towns Ebensburg, Munster, Cresson and then Hollidaysburg/Altoona. A light dome to the southeast may be the result of Breezewood, but it does not extend more than 10 degrees above the horizon. The largest impact was to the east where the light dome from Blue Knob Ski Resort extended upwards to 60+ degrees. It is believed snow-making was in progress - any lights illuminating the area would have reflected off of the snow making the sky appear much brighter. Skies were very transparent. Some structure in the Milky Way was still evident to the northwest and faded just above the tree tops.
LocationComment: Rural location. Chappells Field is a large open area surrounded by either ridges or stands of trees. Depending on the location in the field, they near unobstructed horizon view would appear to be to the south.

SkyComment: Milky Way had fair amount of complex structure with patches and voids noted. Southern ridges helped to block a great deal of sky glow.
LocationComment: Semi-rural location, Little Buffalo State Park

SkyComment: 100% Clear, Transparent sky. Milky Way had fair amount of complex structure with patches and voids noted. Southern ridges helped to block a great deal of sky glow.
LocationComment: Grassy area NW of Pool/Pavillion area. Semi-rural location

SkyComment: 95% Clear, minor small clouds. Light dome extended above southern ridge from the far eastern and western extents with the strongest concentration to the southeast 5 to 10 degrees above ridgetop or 15 to 20 degrees above the horizon. This is presumably from the cities of Harrisburg, Camp Hill/Mechanicsburg, and Carlisle. The only significant outdoor park lighting was in the marina parking lot. Residential neighborhoods do surround the park but any light is dim and or blocked by tree cover.
LocationComment: Dam area of Holman Lake. Area to the south of the dam area was bounded by a ridge extending 10 to 15 degrees.

SkyComment: 100% Clear. A light dome extends from eastern horizon to southwest horizon (5 to 10 degrees above ridgetops), with the greatest concentration of light seen to the southeast, presumably from the city of Chambersburg. An outdoor utility light was on near the concession stand at the beach area. Some light does spill out onto the grassy area, but is somewhat blocked by trees in places. There is some headlight influence as traffic approaches the park from Stumpy Lane or travels along Aughwick Road. Darkest areas are to the west and north. All ridge tops surrounding the area were visible. Bright strobe light seen to the SSW across the lake - presumably from a cell tower. Otherwise area is appreciably dark. Hand placed at arm's length in front of observer was plainly visible.     Summer portion of Milky Way (in Cygnus) was plainly visible to the northwest with structure extending to near overhead. Milky Way faded to the east just above the constellation of Orion (toward the area of skyglow). The Andromeda Galaxy was nearly overhead and plainly visible to the unaided eye.
LocationComment: Dam area of Cowans Gap Lake. Light north wind from 5 to 10 mph. Clear/Dry conditions.  Area to the east and west is bounded by ridges and trees to the north. The southeast horizon is bounded by a low ridge which opens up to the south-southwest when viewed from the dam across the lake.

SkyComment: There were clouds covering more than half the sky, making the stars in Orion's belt less visible.  I could, however,  clearly see a few stars in Orion's belt with magnitudes of 1 or 2. They were bright and stood out despite the presence of clouds. There was contrast between light and dark in the sky as well. Three of the stars were in a slight pattern; they were in a row. I think that due to the many  clouds I was not able to see any color in the sky or symmetry in  patterns of stars. I believe the faintest star I could see was in the 3rd magnitude. This was not a great night to look at the sky. I’m sure on a clearer night I would be able to see far more faint stars.

Tonight the sky conditions looked fairly cloudy by more then 1/2. This is understandable with the weather we experienced today. The afternoon being only 1/4 of the sky cloudy at times then a weather change in the early evening. I was only able to make out the magnitude to about two or three. I had trees obstructing some of my view from a distance but the stars were visable from my home. With much of our week being rainy weather, i was glad to finally get a sighting of Orion. I will continue to look for Orion and hope to be able the beauty of the night sky.

Tonight, I was able to find Orion. However, I went to a field off of West Main St. and sat for a bit and located the constellation. The moon was bright tonight and the air was not completely clear, which made the magnitude higher than we think it normally would be, about a 3 or a 4. I was also able to spot the Big and Little Dippers, two constellations that were fairly easy to locate from the field. Usually the two are very clear, but just like Orion the magnitude was a 3 or a 4. Those were the only three constellations I was able to definitively locate, even with the help of a star map. I feel fortunate to live in an area where we have the opportunity to see stars in a close vicinity because all of these famous constellations are even more fascinating when you can see them yourself. Being able to see things in the sky that people in other parts of the world can see really puts into perspective how big the universe is and how small we are compared to it.

This night was very clear and gave me an incredible view of the night sky.  I feel the clean Colorado air made it an even better experience because there is low amounts of pollution, as well as slightly less atmosphere due to the higher elevation in this area.  For the first time in my life I was able to see the Milky Way galaxy overhead.  During the hour I spent there, I gazed across the entire horizon.  It was nice that the moon was still not in sight to keep even more light off of the stars in the sky.  This experience made me excited and motivated to do this again.
LocationComment: For my dark sky observation, I hopped in a car with some buddies and headed up Flagstaff Road.  Very little light pollution is found up here.  Many trees were in the area but none obstructed my view of the stars.  No obvious man made structures in the vicinity. A small pond was nearby that I was only able to notice while the car headlights were on.  Small traces of snow remained on the ground in a few areas.
Suburban location with a street lamp and trees in the general area.

SkyComment: On 2/04/16, at 21:00, I was out observing while the temperature was 30° F. I was not able to report any clouds or haze in the sky. I spotted the 15° wide soft glow of the Gegenschein without even looking for it while it was only 40° up in between the Sickle of Leo and M44 in Cancer. I believe I might have just caught a glimpse of a magnitude +6.9 star below Betelgeuse, but can’t be certain because of how distractingly bright Betelgeuse was. However, I have proven that on the best nights, I can see stars as faint as magnitude +7.0 overhead. I’ve also proven that the galaxy M81 in Ursa Major is visible with the naked eye on those aforementioned nights. I like to say that I live under high quality Bortle Class 3 skies.
LocationComment: As for other aspects of my observing sight, I live out in the rural where the nearest yard lights are a half mile to my N, NW, and N. From where I observe I am only 15 feet from my house and have about 40° of my western horizon blocked by it and nearby trees. I also have forests covering a chunk of the horizon from the N to the E and all the way S (though the trees come nearest to me in the NE and SE). This is actually a good thing though, since as the nearest cities are in those directions (NNE, E, SE), the worst of their light pollution is blocked from my eyes. The biggest nearby city and thus my worst light-pollution dome is the one 21 miles to the SSE. It’s a noticeable nuisance because there is some good stuff to the south. The darkest and clearest horizon for me is actually in a part of the sky I rarely view – the NW!
